      <body>
         <div type="entry">
                <head>Shalliṭa of Reshʿayna</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Shallita-of-Reshayna</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/502</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">493</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="370"/>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/person/734</idno>
                    <note type="type">person</note>
                    <note type="abstract">
                        <abbr>Bp.</abbr> of Reshʿayna and author of liturgical texts. <note/>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <ab type="infobox">(8th <abbr>cent.</abbr>?) [Ch. of E.]</ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>
                        <abbr>Bp.</abbr> of <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Reshayna">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/172">Reshʿayna</placeName>
                        </ref> and author of liturgical texts. Nothing is known of his
                        life, and his dates are uncertain. The ‘Catalogue’ of <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Abdisho-bar-Brikha">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/310">ʿAbdishoʿ</persName>
                        </ref> (ch. 109) attributes to him various liturgical
                        compositions. Best attested are the long prose prayers in a learned style
                        incorporated into the liturgical collection known as the Abū Ḥalīm (after
                        its compiler, <abbr>Patr.</abbr> Eliya III [1176–90]). A considerable number of these are
                        to be found in T. Darmo’s edition of the <hi rend="italic">Ḥudrā</hi> (vol.
                        I has 17, vol. II has 12). The Shaliṭa who sometimes features in ‘Charms’
                        (<choice>
                            <sic>e.g.</sic>
                            <corr>e.g., </corr>
                        </choice>Gollancz’s <abbr>ms.</abbr> A) will be <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Awgen-Mar">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/356">Mar Awgen</persName>
                        </ref>’s
                        disciple, <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Shalita-Mar">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/733">Shaliṭa</persName>
                        </ref>, and
                        not the <abbr>bp.</abbr>
                    </p>
                </div>
